******
[1] EC-supplied vaccine, Algeria & Tunisia
Date: Mon 4 Aug 2014
From: Keith Sumption <Keith.Sumption@fao.org> [edited]

[ProMED-mail's post 20140802.2654821 of 2 Aug 2014 included a request for information "on the vaccine strain included in the vaccines to be soon supplied by the European Commission to Tunisia and Algeria." We are grateful for the following immediate, firsthand response. - Mod.AS]


The vaccine (to be formulated by Merial) will be trivalent (O/A Iran-05/SAT-2 Eritrea), with minimum potency 6.

The strains have been chosen following vaccine matching results on the circulating O India 2001 topotype, on recent type A strains in Libya/West Eurasia, and relevant SAT2 isolates received by Pirbright in 2013-14.

--
Keith Sumption, Secretary
European Commission for Control of Foot-and-Mouth Disease (EUFMD)
AGAH, FAO, Rome
<Keith.Sumption@fao.org>

[This is good news, particularly since the incorporated FMDV-O strain has, reportedly, been included following vaccine matching results on the circulating "O/ME-SA/Ind-2001 lineage" strain. The need for vaccine matching tests has been raised in the 2 recent EUFMD quarterly reports (see 20140802.2654821).

FMDV "O/ME-SA/Ind-2001 lineage" strain is known to have spread in recent years from the Indian sub-continent into West Eurasia and North Africa (Saudi Arabia, UAE, Libya, Tunisia, Algeria). The availability of an efficient vaccine against this invasive FMD virus strain is of particular importance globally. - Mod.AS]

******
[2] Algeria, economic impact
Date: Mon 4 Aug 2014
Source: Echorouk on line [edited]
http://www.echoroukonline.com/ara/articles/212289.html


The National Union of Algerian Farmers warned of the dangerous spread of foot and mouth disease [FMD], which has infected cattle and livestock. FMD will have an impact on livestock prices, with a remarkable rise ahead of Eid al-Adha in the coming 2 months if the virus spread is not controlled.

Taher Djaref, a member of the National Union of Algerian Farmers, asserted in phone interview with Echorouk that FMD, which has spread recently in many eastern and central cities of Algeria, would affect the prices of sacrificed animals with the approach of Eid al-Adha due to the large loss of sheep and cows because of the spread of the disease, and the deaths of a huge number of cattle and livestock.

"Red meat prices will notice a remarkable rise because of FMD. Government will be forced to import additional quantities of meat from abroad to compensate for the large shortage caused by the disease and to ensure adequate sheep for citizens in Eid al-Adha."

"The Farmers Union rushed to launch an extensive awareness campaign and coordinate with the Ministry of Agriculture for the benefit of cattle ranchers following the announcement of the discovery of the disease in the eastern and central cities of Algeria, and this is to raise awareness about the dangers of FMD and [instruct] them on how to deal with the disease by isolating the infected cattle from the rest of healthy cattle."

"It is better not to allow [contact] between the cattle in the markets and take all the necessary precautions, especially [to vaccinate them]. The Ministry of Agriculture has stepped up its efforts to curb the spread of the disease to the rest of the states. Algeria's veterinary services announced an emergency since the early hours of the disease's discovery in the area of Bir Laarche in Setif (eastern Algeria), where cows' dead bodies were discovered. After the preview, authorities cordoned off the area and closed livestock markets."

"Livestock owners should report on the cases if they see symptoms of the disease in their cows or sheep and call the veterinary services, and then separate the infected cattle from the rest of the cattle so as not to infect more animals. Government will compensate all the peasants who face a loss by 100 percent for every cow infected with FMD, as the Agriculture Ministry will grant 80 percent of the real market price and 20 percent for each cow that is slaughtered and sold as red meat."

[Byline: Ilhem Boutheldji. English version: Dalila Henache]

--
